Soon after a player opens (Opener) the other seats receive specific designations. For example in the above auction North gets "Immediate Seat and/or the Direct Seat" designation. East is the responder and South gets the "Balancing Seat" designation which is the focus of this presentation.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


sb|s|NT|^B@2
The player in the Balancing seat has the option of either bidding the third Pass, which ends the auction, or to take some additional action in order to increase the level of play by the opponents and/or to compete for his side. Therefore, all bids, including double at that seat are considered ^*bbalancing^*N bids.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|^B@2

Further, from the bidding as is shown above, South has the following information which Howard will outline in the next panel.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||BT||
ht|b|cs|6|cp|4|at|^-{|ia|1hpp?|at|}
^-|ht|f|CP||CS||at|
^bFrom the above auction we can gather the following information:

^b@2a) It is known that East has 5 HCP or less

^B@2b) South knows nothing about opener's hand other than he has 5 hearts, less than a 2@C opener, and did not open 1N or 2N. That still leaves a wide range of possible hands. There is a difference than if Opener bid 1@C or 1@D. There, it is possible (although not that likely) that Opener only has a 3-card suit. And he often will have only a 4-card suit. So on this auction, you do know that Opener has some protection in that his suit is real.

^B@2c) Generally partner (direct seat) will have less than 15 or so. With 15+, partner almost always takes some action, even an imperfect one.

^B@2d) South know that your side has at least 16 or 17 HCP between them, usually much more. Opener has no more than 20, responder no more than 5. So theoretically they could have 25, But a practical absolute max for them is 23, leaving at least 17 for the other side-South's side. The main point is that, at worst, the HCP are pretty evenly divided and more often than not South's side has the majority of HCP.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|^B@2

