stanira3: is that an OBAR bid?|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|OBAR stands for "Opponents Bid And Raise". It is Bergen's method of getting into the auction when it goes 1x-p-2x-?. His theory is that whichever person is short in the opponents suit should get into the auction. |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, if it is your turn to bid after 2x, and you are short in suit x, you should bid if you possibly can. You can overcall a good suit or you can make a takeout double. A third alternative that Bergen recommends is to bid 2N, which is takeout for the 2 lower unbid suits (usually the minors), similar in concept to what I discussed above. |
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Absent an agreement that you are playing 2N as a Bergen OBAR 2N, that would be unusual, showing 5/5. But Bergen feels (and I agree) that you should get into the auction even with less distribution, so 2N should show 5/4 or possibly even 4/4.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| Bergen also calls OBAR bids "pre-balancing" because the person who bids directly over 2x is not showing strength, just shortness in suit x and a willingness to compete. Partner of the bidder should not get too excited because, just as with normal balancing, the OBAR bidder is bidding on the combined partnership assets and is assuming even if his hand is not that strong, his partner's must be.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


mb|p|mb|3C|mb|3S|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand, as you will see shortly, since they make 3@S it did not matter that I balanced. But on some hands, they can make 2 but not 3. You rarely get a good score when the opponents stop in 2 with an 8-card fit, so you should strain to balance. "If they have a fit" you have a fit.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Let us look at the math. If they have an 8 card fit, you only have 5 cards in their suit between your hand and partners. So you have 21 cards in the other 3 suits. It is barely possible that you have 3 7-card fits (3 x 7 = 21). However, odds strongly favor an 8 or even 9 card fit as on this hand. And my competitive bidding rules say it is ok to bid 3 over 2 with an 8 card fit, even though it does not meet the LOTT.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


