st||pn|Balancing Seat, Opener,Direct Seat,Responder|md|2,,,|sv|n|RH||AH|A12 - Balancing|AH|How strong is partner's hand|mb|1hpp?|NT|^B@2
Another reason for making a balancing bid is to protect partner when he has good values, but did not have a descriptive bid available in the direct seat. Therefore, it is important to know how strong is partner's hand.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Conventional wisdom has it that when the opponents pass out a one level bid, you can probably assume that on average, your side will have about one half of the points. Your side will have 20-22 points and the opponents will have 18-20 points. (14-16 for opener, 4 for his partner). Subtract your High Card Points from your side's 20-22 to determine partner's points-but hardly ever above 17 points. Those are probably just educated guesses.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Further, there are times that partner's pass is a "trap pass"-has a strong hand and length in opener's suit. At 1 level you possibly can figure out how many trumps partner has. In this example, assuming opener has five hearts and the responder has 2, your side could have about 6 hearts. Subtract the number of cards you have from 6 to determine partner's length in that suit-partner could have about 5 hearts.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


NT|^B@2
In the example as is shown above|MD|0sk974h3caj74dqt93,0,0,0|
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


at| partner is likely to have 5 hearts. Therefore, he probably converts the double by South to a penalty double. However, those assumptions as mentioned are conventional wisdom. For a more realistic calculation let us listen to Howard next. |
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|While it is true, with a singleton heart, that partner is more likely to have hearts, it is not true on average your side will have 6 hearts. You have no idea how many hearts either side has. Opener could easily have 6  hearts and occasionally will have 7 or (rarely) 8.|
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|And let's say opener has 5 hearts. That leaves 8 between the other 3 hands. You have 1, leaving 7 for North and East. On average, partner will have 3.5 hearts (half of the 7 remaining hearts) meaning the opponents have an average of 8.5 hearts even if opener has 5 hearts (and opener could easily have more). I grant you that when responder has 4 hearts he will jump to 3@H if playing Bergen raises. If responder has 5 hearts he will jump to 4@H. So that means it is slightly less likely that responder has 4 or 5 hearts and slightly more likely he has 3 or fewer hearts.|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|If opener has 6 hearts and you have a singleton, on average their side will have a 9-card fit. So once opener opens 1@H, it is quite likely that their side has 8 or more hearts when you have a singleton.|
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Nevertheless, you should still stretch to balance with shortness in opener's suit, for the same reason you always stretch to compete when short in their suit-your hand is worth more on offense when you are short. But it is very unlikely partner has 5 hearts.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Even with the likelihood that partner has a lot of hearts, defending 1@H doubled will rarely net you a good result. Because, if you beat it 2, which is pretty hard, you often can make 3N, which will get you more points. It is likely at best you will get an average result, and often below average.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|In summary, if you're short in opener's suit, stretch to balance. It's more likely partner has the stronger hand-his length in their suit may well be the reason he couldn't bid.|mb|x|
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


NT||
%%A13
st||pn|Balancing Seat, Opener,Direct Seat,Responder|md|2,,,|sv|n|RH||AH|A13 - Balancing|AH|How strong is partner's hand|mb|1hpp?|NT|^B@2
On the other hand strongly consider passing if you have length in opener's suit|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


md|0hk9743s3caj74dqt9|AT| as with the hand as is shown above.|MB|P|
