%%A14
st||pn|Balancing Seat, Opener,Direct Seat,Responder|md|2,,,|sv|n|RH||AH|A14 - Balancing|AH|Vulnerability is Supreme|mb|1hpp?|NT|^B@2
Bidding in balancing seat is literally a balancing act and battling for part score contract. If you bid more than you should and get doubled while vulnerable you lose way more points than opponents could collect making a part score. You have room for safety when not vulnerable and the opponents are. Be conservative when you are vulnerable and they are not-as is now.|
PG| ***** 71 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Further, Howard strongly stressed the following:|
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


AT|

"You will rarely get doubled in a part score, particularly once it goes 1x-p-p. In fact, the fewer points you have, the better positioned your side is to do well. Since your side usually has at least half the deck, if you have fewer points, that means your partner has more points. And your partner's points are well positioned behind the opponent with most of the points."|
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


NT|^B@2
"Your finesses are all going to work. Although it is counter intuitive, it is actually worse if the balancer has a pretty good hand with the majority of the partnership assets, because, by the same reasoning. most of the opponents strength is behind your side's strength, meaning your finesses all rate to lose."|
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


